Principal Component Analysis

# splitting data into train and test
set.seed(1706)
split <- createDataPartition(y = data$funding_total_usd, p = 0.7, list = F, groups = 100)
train_data <- data[split,]
test_data <- data[-split,]
# dropping outcome variable 'funding_total_usd' from train and test
train <- subset(train_data, select = -c(funding_total_usd))
test <- subset(test_data, select = -c(funding_total_usd))

Determine Number of Components

1. Scree Plot

pca_facto = PCA(train, graph = F)
fviz_eig(pca_facto, ncp = 11, addlabels = T)

suggests 6 components

Describe Components

Based on the above analysis, we run PCA with components = 6

pca_facto = PCA(train, scale.unit = T, ncp = 6, graph = F)

Determining the loadings of variables onto the components
